title: For Sale:  "Condemned" Colt Cavalry SAA .45 W/Colt Letter 45 A Fabulous Colt SAA From Jackson Armory!
postcontent: Condemned Colt 7 ½” Cavalry SAA .45W/Colt Letter. Stock # SA3-CEE. Serial # 33277. For the very Advanced Collector, this is a 7 ½” Colt SAA in .45 Colt Caliber. Made in 1876, the pistol was originally sold to the US Military as an “Cavalry” SAA. It was rejected by the Military Inspectors, and sent back to Colt. Colt re-worked the gun, and then sent it to J.P Moores Co in New York for resale on the Civilian Market. The pistol comes with a Colt factory letter that shows the shipment in 1876. The pistol still has a 7 ½” barrel, and the original wooden grips, there is a faint Military Inspector’s marking on the butt of the right grip. The pistol has the Colt Patent Dates, as well as a “US” marking on the left side of the receiver, it also has the # “3351” stamped in that area. The pistol has Colt’s Hartford address on top of the barrel. It also has an interesting 5 notches cut on the left side of the barrel, and also on the butt of the right grip. All the finish is missing, the pistol has patina and areas of very mild freckling, the grips show commensurate wear, the bore is somewhat dark with some visible marking. The cylinder retains all 4 cocks and locks up tightly. This is a excellent Colt SAA that will enhance a great collection! This is an antique firearm – if it is legal for you to own this weapon where you live, and with a copy of your Drivers License, establishing that you are over age 21, we can ship the rifle direct to your home, an FFL License is not required.Questions & Bidding: Please contact us with specific questions BEFORE bidding on an item.

title: For Sale:  1960's Weatherby Mark XXII 22 with beautiful dark wood
postcontent:
This is a nice Weatherby Mark XXII Deluxe made in the late 1960's according to a call to Weatherby. It was one of the earliest Japan version with beautiful aged dark wood stock with gorgeous Rosewood inlays / tips and the white diamond under the pistol grip. My understanding is that this is the rare KTG version between the Italian Berretta version but prior to Nikko Kodensha in Japan taking over and then Mossberg and eventually Howa. It comes with a five rounds magazine. It has a very nice adjustable trigger that is light and crisp. My guess would be about a 2.5 lb trigger. It has a jeweled bolt and smooth action. It has the factory flip down rear sight set for different yardages. Another unique feature of this rifle is the fact you can shoot it in semi-auto mode or single shot. The single shot is great for new shooters or for training an experienced shooter to take their time between shots. The receiver looks nice and the barrel has a deep and dark blue to it. There are small spots where the blue is missing and some pitting set in at one point. The wood has nice checkering and a beautiful aged wood tone to it. There is a small hairline crack on the top where it meets the receiver. You can twist on it and the crack does not open up at all so i don't think it will effect the performance.
